17f9b78129866dff3cbd228a8d985fbf: [Microsoft] is d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7 17f9b78129866dff3cbd228a8d985fbf, [Microsoft] is d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7 scribe: d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7 scribeNick: d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: Not clear before that this was a requirement for this spec. .. Does not appear to be difficult to implement 0c8dce20967cf80665e60051b8ab2d3c: Linux could be a problem, this info may not be exposed.. 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: For platforms that do expose this info, it doesn't seem like it would be difficult to implement .. Depending on the platform, it may not be available/dependable. ... May not be accurate in all scenarios. ... as a heuristic, content authors are willing to say good enough. d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: We can spec it such that if the platform/OS doesn't support providing this info, then the value could be null (n/a) 0c8dce20967cf80665e60051b8ab2d3c: Where is the keyboard layouts defined? 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: Couldn't find a standard for reporting the keyboard layout--also couldn't find something for the keybaord language. ... I could have an English Dvorak keyboard! ... For the language, I think we should just go with en-US style ... (Can't think of the term for this format) ... BCP47 tag d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: Notes that "navigator.systemLanguage" returns a similar language code: "en-us" 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: Probably requires a list of conversions from OS-defined langauge codes to BCP-47 ... (normalized) d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: Related to the issue, I have a preference that the keyboard lang info be provided as a global property (on document?) and that we create an event that notifies of changes (which are not expected to occur very frequently) d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: Not sure I understand the threat. 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: It allows profiling of users d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: I would argue that the navigator object allows a higher-degree of profling (see navigator.platform in HTML5) ... Also, my goal is to limit the amount of information we provide in the event that is largely redundant. 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: If you copy/paste something, the input-locale could be different than if the user is just typing text. travis: good point. 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: In order to specify this correctly... consider: ... when something is copied, is the source language prerved? s/prerved/preserved/ ... does this impose a requirement on an OS? d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: What's the scope? 0c8dce20967cf80665e60051b8ab2d3c: TextInput and Keyboard events. 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: Sounds like we have accepted this comment. RESOLUTION: Accept issue 119, and add inputLocale to TextInput and Keyboard events. Topic: Issue 120 move scroll from UIEvent to Event 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: I think it logically belongs in UI events, even if it traditionally hasn't been a UIEvent, I don't see how it breaks. ... it might be argued that is sends extraneous information (null/ empty string) ... Any code that characterizes events based on its interface, it makes more sense to make it a UIEvent. ... Makes it consistent with our model. d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: I have no argument for or against this issue. 0c8dce20967cf80665e60051b8ab2d3c: Same here. 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: It is a non-goal for me to document the behavior as it exists in browsers today. ... my goal is to create a consistent and logical model that forms a solid foundation for future events and content. ... Since the folks on the call don't have a strong opinion, then I'd like to keep this event the way it is. RESOLUTION: Keep scroll as a UIEvent, pending further feedback from implementors Topic: Issue 121: generalize textInput to cover all user-initiated changes Note: Jacob Rossi joins the call from d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7' phone 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: This sounds like mutation events. JRossi: textInput sounded like the catch-all for input, without the rest of this requests in the Issue. d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: Notes that the "input" event exists that covers more of these cases (removals of characters, addition of characters, etc.) 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: I'm interested in deferring this request, and not doing this in DOM L3 Events. ... I'd like to propose that we keep it the way it is for now. If we decide to accept this workitem, that it could be a standalone spec that adds the new event and details the new event exhaustively, it's relationship to textInput, etc. ... By adding it into this spec, we may not get the implementation feedback that we've had so far. ... Based on the details of how this new event would be speced, it could be compared to textInput. JRossi: Could we consider changing the name? from textInput to beforeInput. d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: This event is already implemented (for some time) in WebKit and now in IE9. 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: On the surface this proposal (Issue 212) seems pretty complex (with lots of cases). RESOLUTION: counter-propose that the beforeInput event be a separate event that is defined in its own spec. Topic: Issue 122 add mousewheel event back. d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: The mousewheel event was originally pulled from this spec because we (Microsoft) felt that mousewheel didn't 1) convey all the information that was appropriate for a future-looking wheel event, 2) scenarios covered by mosuewheel are also covered by wheel event, 3) implementation support for mousewheel is spotty (not available in Mozilla's Firefox). 0c8dce20967cf80665e60051b8ab2d3c: mousewheel doesn't have all the features. JRossi: only one-direction scrolling, doesn't handle pixel/line/etc. ... Also confusing from a consistency (intra-spec) to have both events. 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: A lot of existing content special-cases mousewheel and other wheel-related events. ... If we specified it, and browsers changed their implementations, existing content might break. ... better to let it fade with time and exist in specific implementations idiosyncratic-ly. (known spelling issue <---) RESOLUTION: The group will not re-add mousewheel event back to the spec. Topic: Issue 126: isTrusted 0c8dce20967cf80665e60051b8ab2d3c: I believe we used 'trusted' because of alignment with XBL2 d5217991a5c7374b110deb03905676f7: 'trusted' has the same semantic meaning as 'isTrusted'. RESOLUTION: Change 'trusted' to 'isTrusted' :-) Topic: Plans for TPAC 227a9a17d1db3f8e5c71a150345fb2a6: Wondering who's attending. ... Please register as quickly as possible if you are planning on attending!!!!!j (j is near Enter) (well not really)

Question r/e <track>. The spec currently says "The src attribute gives the address of the time track data. The value must be a valid non-empty URL potentially surrounded by spaces. This attribute must be present." Can it not be optional if there is a descendent <source> element, so that different formats can be fed to different browsers (a la <video> itself)? True, we don't want separate formats for anything. But it doesn't look like there's much agreement on such things as formats? (And what happens when Hixie's children dream up WebSRT+ or something like that?) isn't the obvious migration path t .. to make it like video itself and allow descendent <source> elements? Speccing that now while there are no implementations would seem to be better edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e, is there an idea of what webSRT file suffix will be, eg is it <track kind=captions src=blah.wsrt> ? edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e, thanks. By the way, I'm planning to use your line "designing for a theoretical future always goes wrong" to explain to my wife why I'm buying a vintage Les Paul guitar instead of putting some money aside for my daughter's school fees. edb259c0e0038f38bb200bc20c8cbf7e you're on. We'll play it over a few pints of your Jenever beer. f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220, she might turn out not to be bright enough for Uni; there might be some kind of apocalypse before that (I recently watched a documentary called 2012 about all the bad things that might happen). philosophically, all future is theoretical, I guess. Whereas vintage Les Pauls are tangible. In fact, they weigh a bloody tonne f139aba52f9fa1394b4034a7954b2220, in the socialist utopia that is the UK, schools are free. Except for aristocrats who go to exclusive fee-paying schools called (counter-inuituively) "public school". But I confused the issue of shamefully using the American way of referring to higher education as "school". I'll be saying "awesome" next we had it in the UK; finished just after I graduated. Hopefully no cause and effect there

depends on what you mean with HA you can put oracle xe on a shared disk system and have an active/passive setup or use poor mans dataguard (scripts to sync logfiles and apply) sure no problem as long as you have the backend to support it no a good scsi array will do fine take a dell 220 with dual cluster compatible controllers and raid cards (perc4dc) or a hp msa array... or ibm exp yes yes and no... it is very very unlikely that the array will fail so badly that it will cause downtime you have two controllers in the array the only non-redundant part will be the backplane and the enclosure itself i don't think i've ever seen a normal scsi backplane die use two arrays if you are paranoid... performance will be quite sucky tho and you need a cluster aware software raid solution (vxvm) or gfs from redhat/centos i'm implementing a small ha system in a few weeks... two dell 2950's and a dell ax150 array.. very cheap SE and redhat cluster server with ocfs most basic raid controllers don't support split bus mirroring... i have asked hp and dell about it... you can't use four raid cards and two arrays in HW mode :( you can probably use two cards with dual ports tho... thats probably a decent solution hm, asm should be able to do it when i think of it using mirroring in asm.. should be a quite clean solution without cluster filesystems and extra software raid layers...
you can probably do a mirrored disk situation with two cabinets without a clustered filesystem though I agree with hali, that's pretty paranoid right, not in hw mode it'd be software

Consider the following the HTML 4 snippet: <table><col width="90"><col width="200"><col width="50"><tr><td style="background: blue">Col. 1</td><td colspan="2" style="background: red">Span cols 2 and 3</td></tr></table> Notice there are three <col> elements. What should the computed width of each <td> be? 90 and 250, respectively? By subsection The COL element of section 11.2.4 of the HTML 4.01 spec. <http://www.w3.org/TR/html4/struct/tables.html#h-11.2.4.2> a <col> element may have an attribute called span, which is the number of column that share the same attributes described by the <col> element. It is unclear to me what should happen with respect to inheriting (if that is even the right word) the <col> attributes, when the <td> specifies a colspan (as in the aforementioned example) Is this case even valid? hi hixie 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: For your reference, this question is with respect to https://bugs.webkit.org/show_bug.cgi?id=14858 We may be able to simplify this question to (haven't checked the spec. yet on this):  Does declaring a colspan value > 1 increase the effective number of columns in the table? Consider the example: <table><tr><td colspan="2">Physical column 1</td></tr></table> There is one <td> ("physical column") in the table. Do we interpret this table as having two "effective" columns? 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: But in the HTML 5 spec. <col> can have a style attribute (as inherited from the list of global attributes), so this case still possible (substitute style="width: Xpx" for the HTML 4 width attribute, width="X" in the above example)? hi 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884, yes, I agree it is unclear 139513027e8e90b5582cbc68fc733884: for your reference, both Firefox and IE will render the <td colspan="2"> element with a width around 250 in the above example (disregarding border and padding) Note, WebKit only handles this case differently (i.e. when there is only one row whose number of <td> is less than the number of column implied by the colspans)
HTML4 is kinda vague about this stuff and doesn't really match reality anyway and HTML5 makes width="" on <col> invalid so hard to say :-)

I've always emulated <figure> with <div>, not <span> so it seems weird to me to want <figure> as a child of <p> the way <p> auto-closes is weird, but it's not going away. given that, it seems like new elements should behave like their closest-analog old elements. so <section> auto-closes <p> because <div> does, etc. we at least want the language to cohere. given that <div> and the other old "block" elements auto-close <p>, as an author I expect <article> to, and would be (even more) weirded out if it didn't. I mean, I can at least sort-of make sense of the legacy auto-closing. If <article> didn't auto-close <p>, suddenly the weird-but-kinda-makes-sense auto-closing rules are even less predictable

How can I keep Apache 1.3 from appending trailing slashes when the web client asks for a directory? (Yes, I know this is normally desirable, but in this case I really do want it off.) mod_rewrite wouldn't do it, because Apache would put the trailing slash back. Tried it already. But using [R] is the whole point... I want the canonical form of the URL to be without the slash. (The reason is I'm experimenting with a URL scheme that doesn't distinguish files and directories.) suv4x4 - no idea how to do it, though? I heard Apache got a directive for exactly this sort of thing, but since the server's not mine, I can't upgrade Apache to use it :( suv4x4 - well, thanks anyways... I actually have a solution that works except that .htaccess files won't work in subdirectories... but I'd like it if they did. mst - what I mean is, for example, a request for /foo/bar will get rewritten to /index.php?q=foo/bar, and then index.php will read in something from /impl/foo/bar... if I have /impl/foo/.htaccess, Apache's not going to realize it "should" use that .htaccess file. It'd need to be at /foo and not /impl/foo The point of the /impl directory is actually to hide the directory structure from Apache to keep it from appending trailing slashes when a directory is specified in the URL (to put it another way: to decouple the URL from the filesystem somewhat) If I did rewriting so that Apache would find the .htaccess files, it would also append trailing slashes again, I think. Unless I did things in a way even more convoluted than I am now, perhaps... (which I don't want to do) mst - oh, I see you missed the part where I was talking about removing trailing slashes from my URLs Well, the .htaccess in a subdirectory is to use further rewrite rules that only apply to that subdirectory, so that, say, /foo/bar/baz gets rewritten to /foo/bar.php?q=baz But I don't want that in my root .htaccess. I could live with it there if I had to Why would I want what, exactly? mst - I don't have access to that. Shared hosting. I figure if I have to use .htaccess, I may as well use it to its full advantage... Really, though, I'd prefer a better means of keeping Apache from appending trailing slashes to directory names in the first place... then I wouldn't need to put things in the /impl subdirectory to hide the directory names. I'm guessing there's no other practical way to do it... I could easily be wrong, of course. (Heh, I know the whole idea seems pretty absurd, and in a way it is, but...) well, thanks edgy - why do you have index.html and index.php in the same directory in the first place? Why not just rename the .php file then? (Note that I don't actually know the answer to your question, sorry) Yeah, I can understand that. It sounds to me that .php just has a higher priority, like a content negotiation type thing (though I don't know if it's actually handled by the content negotiation module) edgy - I know, I do the same thing edgy - I felt I still had to ask, though :) (Likewise, I get "Why do you want to do that?" when I ask about how to keep Apache from appending trailing slashes to directory names...) I don't suppose you'd know anything about that, BTW :P Heh, maybe, maybe not :) Since usually having an index.html and index.php in the same directory isn't good form anyway, just as chopping off the trailing slash of directory names isn't usually good form But that doesn't keep us from wanting to do those things because 'usually' isn't 'always' edgy - it's an Apache issue because it's the webserver I'm wrestling with to try to get it to stop doing that. :) Yeah. I want it to just stay /foo And I'm not funkywizard... ;) mst - can that be done from within .htaccess, though? Yeah, I am. If I weren't, I'd just use Apache 2.x and use mod_dir's DirectorySlash directive But I'm stuck on 1.3 Heh, it's actually no big deal (and if it were just any old website, I wouldn't even worry about it), but this is for my own, personal website, which means I get even more obsessive-compulsive about getting things just the way I want them than normal I feel that a trailing slash doesn't actually provide useful information. It means "There might be more information on a deeper level... but then again, there might not." Not very useful. Other than that, it's merely an implementation detail.

jgraham: Oh, okay 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: It seems to be defined at a very inconvenient level of abstraction - someone implementing the vCard output would have to have access to the DOM and the item-extraction algorithm, rather than it being layered on top of a generic microdata extraction algorithm Someone who's writing a generic microdata parsing library doesn't want to have to implement the vCard output (and iCal and BibTeX and ...) themselves, because the point is to be generic and not hard-code lots of vocabularies and someone who's working with vCard data will want to use the generic microdata parsing library rather than rewriting everything themselves, and doesn't want to have to hook into internal details of the library (like whether the <title> element is going to be exposed via DOM or SAX or something else) so there should be some clearly specified API between them, e.g. using JSON as an intermediate format (and giving a single JSON-to-vCard or RDF-to-vCard or something-else-to-vCard conversion algorithm, depending on what API is chosen) 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: The RDF output is not vocabulary-specific, so that should go in the generic library (which can happily deal with all the issues like extracting <title> elements) I don't think it has to be a serialised API like JSON, but it seems useful to have some clearly specified API that can be easily implemented by the generic library and is powerful enough to let vocabulary designers do whatever they want without having to modify the generic library And the document's current address thinks the JSON and RDF outputs are fine where they are, because they're not vocabulary-specific and so we don't have to worry about the scalability of implementing a thousand of them in the library I also wish we had a specification that said what was a bug and what was correct 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e: The comments seem unresolvable in an HTML4+RDFa specification, and nobody has shown great interest in writing an HTML5+RDFa specification, so I don't know where the comments would get addressed At least Shane's statement that "The goal here is that all implementations extract the same collection of triples from a given document." sounds exactly like the goal of an HTML5+RDFa specification (as long as it's not restricted to valid documents, or to static documents) I think that counts as "unresolvable" :-p s/unresolvable/practically unresolvable/ Sure so HTML4+RDFa is impractical and seems quite pointless, because all it really provides is a DTD, and you could use an XHTML DTD instead if you just want validation But his stated goal suggests that he might be receptive to an HTML5+RDFa specification, since it's the only way to achieve his stated goals, so that suggests it could be possible to move in the right direction in the future s/repetition// (But that seems unlikely to happen unless someone familiar with HTML5 writes it, because anyone else would find it very hard to understand the HTML5 processing model in enough detail without spending ages learning it) Defining an HTML processing model for RDFa is kind of diving in the deep end - it's not a nice gradual learning curve, and so people are more likely to ignore it and stick with what they're familiar with b8810fee2f4a71f849f3f7409546d1d9: You should use ECC memory

do generic RDF tools do anything useful? (I honestly don't know) It does seem that in some cases people use generic RDF tools to extract information which they then process in a vocabulary-specific way I think the kind of tool I described couldn't possibly be an end-user tool, or at least not a good one because you can't make a good UI for displaying "generic" data I'm not sure everyone agrees that HTML is the Web's most core language that seems harder to dispute :-) (though people have certainly tried to claim that public deployment numbers are not representative of what you'd find if you could survey intranets) I would generally agree with that sentiment, if only for methodological reasons it is very easy to make unverifiable claims about the contents of intranets I do think specific claims about intranet content that are supported by evidence may be worth considering even if not at the same weight as the public Web since a controlled environment has less need for open-ended interoperability so maybe it's just me, but Sam often seems to have more interesting things to say about what's going on in the HTML WG on his blog than in public-html

I believe they use lots and lots of overloading instead It depends on the case, though Like doing send() in XMLHttpRequest instead of send(null) is not something to fail over RGB except when it's BGR...

Anything that ends with arguments which could accept 'undefined' could be counted as having optional arguments http://www.whatwg.org/specs/web-apps/current-work/#the-2d - drawImage has lots of overloading Oh, I misremembered the too-few-arguments things - it says "Unless other specified, if a method is passed fewer arguments than is defined for that method in its IDL definition, a NOT_SUPPORTED_ERR exception must be raised." (though that's not standard JS behaviour so maybe it should be changed) drawImage discriminates on HTMLImageElement vs HTMLCanvasElement createPattern too (I'm not familiar with any examples outside the canvas API, though) Hmm, would it be good if there was a way for the APIs to complain about errors without using exceptions, so the script could carry on regardless? because it's nice to know when you've done something wrong, so reporting errors is good Multiple returns are easy in JS 1.7 :-) (But people ignore error codes by default, so they don't seem a good way to tell authors when they've done something wrong) I think I remember hearing of someone having found that they could fix lots of crashes in C programs by just returning 0 for any invalid memory reads, and the programs usually carried on correctly even though the data was rubbish (...but I don't know (and can't find) any actual details) My assumption would be that a gradient from (a,b,c,d) to (e,f,g,h) would have colour ((a+e)/2,(b+f)/2,...) at the centre, in the same colour space as all the input/output colours (via fillStyle, get/putImageData, etc) but the colour space is undefined (and it seems implementations use 'device RGB' rather than e.g. sRGB) so you can't really tell what it'll look like in which case it doesn't matter that the linear interpolation is not exactly defined, since it relies on other things are even less defined (but all those things ought to be defined eventually) I'm not either, but I can't think of any other way of interpolating colours that makes sense :-) I suppose you could claim that since it says "the colors and the alpha component must be ..." rather than "the color must be ...", it means to split out the four components because otherwise it'd use the simpler phrasing

ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: yeah, I think the too few arguments rule is a bad one ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: JS exceptions are bad sort of for the same reason as draconian parsing rules minor implementation differences turn into fatal errors in some browsers but not all a3f19f90edf0a0893c7847d08016abe3: I wish I could claim it's possible for browser vendors not to make mistakes ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: well, the other common approach is to return an error code, but multiple returns in JS are awkward ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c: I think logging a warning would be the best thing for browsers to do on wrong number of args (too few or too many) probably not good to rely on random mozilla-specific extensions to JS a3f19f90edf0a0893c7847d08016abe3: you'd be surprised a3f19f90edf0a0893c7847d08016abe3: a lot of the time, silent failure leads to a script that is very close to working right I'm not talking about my personal code, but code that I tend to see on the web a lot of pages that fail catastrophically are due to getting a JS exception in Safari and not in other browsers a3f19f90edf0a0893c7847d08016abe3: often methods or properties that are missing, scope differences, differences in expected parameters, etc a3f19f90edf0a0893c7847d08016abe3: a lot of the time just commenting out the offending line of JS leads to a page that mostly works a3f19f90edf0a0893c7847d08016abe3: I don't know much about the Qt port shrugs on Windows, 'device RGB' and sRGB are for pratical purposes the same thing though not on mac, since the gamma is different

hello 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, I'm curious what your proposal is for an http based protocol for TCPConnection? 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e mentioned that the protocol was your main objection 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, Ok, I'm at least interested in the reasons for it 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, I'm putting together a document about the pros and cons of http for TCPConnection ok i had a couple of other concerns With SSL there is no way to do virtual hosting -- you have to route on ip address... HTTP/1.1 upgrade with TLS solves this problem Http provides the Host header to avoid dns rebinding attacks 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, it seems to me the way to do it is send an OPTIONS with an Upgrade: tcp/1.0 header as the client->server tcp handshake also, HTTP based connections include query parameters and cookies, allowing for normal auth mechanisms 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, i'll add your three points to my document the big hurdle is keeping it simple enough for 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e's requirements, particularly that it be possible to implement in just a few lines of perl ab7faae5d7b250ea8606486575f8f79c, he wants it to be 3 lines with no support libraries 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, oh, i think we could get it done in just a few lines of code even if it was http-based 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e, i don't think saying "it should be implementable in 3-10 lines of perl" is unreasonable whatsoever 65325d50b2e25aca54bc871b89758c9c, well, I'm working on a proof of concept so feel free to suggest to me any ideas you have

c4c52ee28b65ac033f57ce478087cfd1: I don't have a full proposal for how to satisfy the TCPConnection use cases my two problems with it are: (1) it uses port/host addressing instead of URI addressing, which is a poor fit for the Web model (2) it's bad to send non-http over the assigned ports for http and https (3) I am worried that connection to arbitrary ports could lead to security issues, although 69b0d3dfe919a6b860a9fac82de52a7e tried hard to avoid them (basically the only security mechanism though is assuming that no other protocol will happen to emulate the TCPConnection handshake, which seems pretty weak) (given that other protocols have been found to have multiple interpretation vulnerabilities) I guess that is three problems c4c52ee28b65ac033f57ce478087cfd1: I think a custom http method that begins a two-way session might be a promising solution, but I think that would require a proof of concept that it is viable on client and server side c4c52ee28b65ac033f57ce478087cfd1: those are also good points c4c52ee28b65ac033f57ce478087cfd1: my vague idea was to repurpose the CONNECT method, since that is likely to already work through proxies c4c52ee28b65ac033f57ce478087cfd1: but developing the proper server-side support would be tricky so I feel like it is not worth suggesting without proof-of-concept client and server impls I think the two-way persistent connection problem may just have to get solved after HTML5

that doesn't quite explain it 100% it doesn't ignore them, it just doesn't have escape code processing there is nevertheless a way to embed a " character into the string without terminating it: just use two of them in a row to get a single character insidet he string the other thing that @ strings can do is embed newlines directly, as in: string two_lines = @"first_line second_line"; it's useful for things like help/usage messages in console applications, and very large messageboxes, and stuff tuxipuxi: er, well, if I'm understanding you correctly, yes :-) er wait, no, you need a @ at the start of the literal :-) string bla = @"bla ""bla"" bla"; without the '@', strings are essentially the same as C/C++/Java these two are equivalent: string bla = @"bla ""bla"" bl"; and string bla = "bla \"bla\" bla"; does that explain it? :-) yep I don't see it as a limitation, though, because it actually makes it *easier* for the majority of strings :-) especially windows-style pahts @"C:\Path\To\File.txt" as opposed to "C:\\Path\\To\\File.txt" which is more readable? :-)
